<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,356,815]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,289,536,562]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Biology</emphasis>
. This species causes a gall on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[644,810,536,562]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Apluda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mutica">
<emphasis box="[644,810,536,562]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Apluda mutica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (
<taxonomicName box="[860,955,537,563]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
) described simply as a leaf sheath gall by 
<bibRefCitation author="Felt, E. P." box="[151,277,572,599]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" pagination="1 - 11" refId="ref58101" refString="Felt, E. P. (1920) New Indian gall midges. Memoirs of the Department of Agriculture in India, 7, 1 - 11." type="journal article" year="1920">Felt (1920)</bibRefCitation>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[348,408,572,598]" name="India" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">India</collectingCountry>
, but later extended by DvLR &amp; Dvl (1926, gall No 52, 
<figureCitation box="[1039,1119,572,599]" captionStart="FIGURES 28" captionStartId="50.[151,264,1484,1508]" captionTargetBox="[157,1430,747,1455]" captionTargetId="figure-287@50.[151,1436,741,1461]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="FIGURES 28a–e. Orseolia graminicola: a, male flagellomere; b, young gall on Cynodon dactylon; c, female flagellomere; d, mature gall on Cynodon dactylon; e, male terminalia (ventral). Figs a, c, e from Kieffer &amp; DvLR 1910), Figs b and d from DvLR &amp; DvL (1926, Figs 29, 30). Arrows indicate galls." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406926" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406926/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
[
<figureCitation box="[1134,1232,572,599]" captionStart="FIGURES 26" captionStartId="48.[151,264,1471,1495]" captionTargetBox="[155,1431,842,1442]" captionTargetId="figure-243@48.[151,1436,838,1447]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURES 26a–b. Orseolia apludae: a, gall on Apluda mutica (arrows indicate galls; Fig. 28 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926)); b, male terminalia (dorsal, cerci omitted, from Gagné 1985). Figs 26c–d. Orseolia graminis: c, gall on Ottochloa nodosa (arrow indicates gall; Fig. 38 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926)); d, last two female flagellomeres (from Kieffer &amp; DvLR (1910))." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406922" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406922/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 26a</figureCitation>
]) who found it on the same host in 
<collectingCountry box="[343,456,608,634]" name="Indonesia" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
. The gall protrudes from the sheath of the youngest leaf. The leaf blade remains undeveloped. The sheath is shaped into a tube enclosing and supporting the growth tip. The gall grows out of the older leaves and buds which develop after the infection and are long and thin, with a slender apex.
</paragraph>
